uring the age of mass migration were aided appreciably by their association with a particular corner of the American economy: the rag trade. From humble beginnings, Jews rode the coattails of the clothing trade from the margins of economic life to a position of unusual promise and prominence, shaping both their societal status and the clothing industry as a whole. Comparing the history of Jewish participation within the clothing trade in the United States with that of Jews in the same business in England, The Rag Race demonstrates that differences within the garment industry on either side of the Atlantic contributed to a very real divergence in social and economic outcomes for Jews in each setting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aClothing tradezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aClothing tradezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszEnglandxEconomic conditionsxHistory. 0aJewszUnited StatesxEconomic conditionsxHistory. 0aSuccess in businesszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSuccess in businesszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107289960 cprintz978147984718140uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479860258.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479860258423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479860258/original  a978-3-11-072899-6  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK